openpas.basics

Interface PropFactory


  • public interface PropFactory
    ProbFactory is the main way to acquire new objects and access singletons that implement the various interfaces in OpenPAS. The objects vary but include: operators, literals, expressions, sentences, and utility objects such as stringers.

      • createProposition

        Proposition createProposition(java.lang.String name,
                              boolean neg)
        Creates the named proposition. An index number is allocated for each new proposition. The way to access the negated version of an existing proposition is to Literal.cloneNegated() it.
        Parameters:
        name - A name to identify this proposition. There's no uniqueness constraint during the creation of literals, but when they're used inside a PAS instance. The name specified must conform to the regular expression as specified in getValidName().
        neg -
        Returns:

      • getPropositions

        java.lang.Iterable<Proposition> getPropositions()
        Returns all known propositions created by this factory. A factory is not required to keep all the literals it creates if the consumer doesn't keep a reference to those objects such that the literals returned by this function may contain as subset of the literals that have been created.

      • createClause

        Expressions.Expression<LogicalOps.LogicalOr> createClause(boolean ordered)
        Creates an empty clause. This may be an ordered clause if specified. A clause is ordered if it retains the insertion order of the literals it contains. This is useful for creating horn clauses where the body and head have special meanings.
        Parameters:
        ordered - True if the newly created clause will be ordered, false otherwise.
        Returns:

      • getHornStringer

        StringOps.LogicalStringer getHornStringer()
        Returns a stringer that's guaranteed to return horn clause representations of a clause or a CNF. This will only work on a clause or a CNF. The stringer may return null when given an expression that's not a clause, or a sentence that's not a CNF.
        Returns:
